Because $\frac{d}{dx} \left( g(x) \right) = 0,$ and the polynomial $g(f(x))$ is divisible by $g(x)$, we have that the remainders of $\frac{g(f(x))}{f(x)}$ and $\frac{g(x^{12})}{g(x)}$ are the same. For $f(x) = x^5 + x^4 + x^3 + x^2 + x + 1,$
\begin{align*}
g(x) f(x) &= f(x) (x+1) (x^2 + x + 1) (x^3 + 1) \\
&= x^6 - 1.
\end{align*}
Thus, we have
\begin{align*}
\frac{g(x^{12})}{g(x)} &= \frac{x^{72} - 1}{x^6 - 1} \\
&= \frac{(x^{12} - 1)(x^{60} + x^{54} + x^{36} + x^{24} + x^{12} + 1)}{(x^6 - 1)} \\
&= (x^{60} + x^{54} + x^{36} + x^{24} + x^{12} + 1),
\end{align*}
where the last factor is $g(x^6).$ Thus, the remainder is 
